	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">My Cockroach Diary</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sparrow">Sparrow</a></li><li><a href="/issues/217">January 1994</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><em>December 7</em><br />
The cockroaches in this apartment have gone beyond all rational number &mdash; they have reached an irrational number. And they no longer wait until midnight to come out; they swarm after dark, at five. Ever since our visit to Russia in 1990, they&rsquo;ve been increasing, and now they outnumber us four thousand to one.</p>

<p>Oh no, I just found one in the saltshaker! I helped it escape, using one of the baby&rsquo;s spoons.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>December 8</em><br />
This morning, three more cockroaches were in the saltshaker, but I couldn&rsquo;t find the baby&rsquo;s spoon. I used a larger spoon, which they refused to climb on. It was sad to see them struggling through the killing salt, dreaming of escape, but avoiding the instrument of salvation.</p>

<p>This must be how Christians see the world, I thought.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>December 9</em><br />
My wife woke up with a cockroach in her ear.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It feels really strange. It&rsquo;s moving around,&rdquo; she said. She tried to take it out with a tissue wrapped around a chopstick.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Let it crawl out,&rdquo; I told her. &ldquo;If you kill it, it&rsquo;ll get stuck in there.&rdquo;</p>

<p>She stopped digging, and fifteen minutes later the bug <em>did </em>crawl out &mdash; a cute baby roach.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Now Violet is cleaning out the insect den under the sink. &ldquo;Sorry, cockroaches. It&rsquo;s just not working out between us,&rdquo; she explains as she wipes away their nests.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It smells of cockroach shit down here,&rdquo; she says to me.</p>

<p>I never knew cockroach shit had a <em>smell</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>December 10</em><br />
Last night went well. There were fewer roaches than I have seen for months &mdash; as few as thirty-three.</p>

<p>But tonight we went to our neighbor&rsquo;s house to watch a video, and when we returned there were thousands again.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s like trying to destroy the Mafia. You can arrest them, but you can&rsquo;t break their organization. These cockroaches have been at it for generations &mdash; it&rsquo;s all they know. The kids go into it because their fathers do it.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>December 13</em><br />
Until now we haven&rsquo;t killed the roaches. We&rsquo;ve employed preventive methods: doing the dishes right away, taking the garbage out daily. Then last night, while washing dishes, I noticed a roach crawling on the side of a cup. I made no effort to save him, and in a moment he had drowned. A certain hardness has crept into me, I realized.</p>

<p>When I bathe now, and notice three or four roach corpses in the tub &mdash; drowned as the water poured in &mdash; I feel a grim satisfaction.</p>

<p>I wonder, &ldquo;Could I kill a man now?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>December 17</em><br />
A cockroach has been trapped in the saltshaker all day, and I&rsquo;ve done nothing. I&rsquo;m bored with liberating them over and over. He walks around while I pour salt out from under him. It&rsquo;s like having a tiny man living in your watch.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 4</em><br />
At our New Year&rsquo;s Eve party, Norman announced, &ldquo;I think you have a roach problem.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why do you say that?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Because I&rsquo;ve seen several roaches walking around next to the food. If roaches come out in the middle of a party, you have a problem.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve already killed six of them,&rdquo; added Violet&rsquo;s cousin Bill.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I bet <em>you </em>don&rsquo;t kill them,&rdquo; Norman accused me. &ldquo;You probably tell them to leave. I had a roommate like that in San Francisco. We lived above a carriage house in an alley, and we had a bad roach problem. He believed that if he told them to leave, they would go. He&rsquo;d say to them, &lsquo;Roaches, please don&rsquo;t stay here. We don&rsquo;t really want you here.&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Did they listen to him?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Of course not. They got worse.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;So what did you do?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I called in the exterminator. He came three times, and then the roaches were gone.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Violet said, &ldquo;But our friend Therese told the cockroaches to leave an apartment, and they left.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; I told Norman. &ldquo;Your friend probably wasn&rsquo;t spiritually evolved enough.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well, the roaches aren&rsquo;t listening to you either!&rdquo; Norman said.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 5</em><br />
I forgot to tell Norman my favorite roach-killing story &mdash; the time a guy came to my door in Washington Heights and asked, &ldquo;Do you want to be exterminated?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 16</em><br />
It&rsquo;s unfortunate that we had our baby, Sylvia, in the middle of this cockroach war, because a baby&rsquo;s job is to eat one-eighteenth of a potato, then throw the rest on the floor for you to step on, and the whole time you&rsquo;re thinking, &ldquo;She&rsquo;s feeding the damn roaches. She&rsquo;s in league with them.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 19</em><br />
Today as I drank some tea I saw a speck floating in it. Is it a baby cockroach? I wondered. I looked more closely, and it seemed benign.</p>

<p>After I finished the tea, I thought, perhaps it <em>was </em>a roach. Maybe I eat cockroaches every day. They run out of a pot of millet sometimes. But does<em> every one</em> run out?</p>

<p>How many roaches a day do I eat?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 21</em><br />
My mother came over to babysit and said, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m having <em>such</em> a roach problem. I got a small garbage can with a tight lid, but it doesn&rsquo;t help. I just can&rsquo;t <em>cope</em> with my roaches anymore!&rdquo;</p>

<p>This reassured me. Perhaps roach problems are hereditary.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 22</em><br />
Today I was working on my novel, and a bug walked out on the desk in front of me. I looked down in anger, then saw it wasn&rsquo;t a roach. It was a gray, horned creature, like a miniature toad. I almost kissed it, out of gratitude.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>January 26</em><br />
&ldquo;Lately when I open the cupboard doors,&rdquo; my wife said, &ldquo;a cockroach usually falls on my head. It&rsquo;s really obnoxious.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve noticed it, too. Are they <em>leaning</em> on the doors more than they used to?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 10</em><br />
Violet woke up with another cockroach in her ear. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really loud,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s walking on my eardrum.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Did you try to take it out?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No. Now it&rsquo;s stopped moving,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Can you look in my ear?&rdquo; (We bought a speculum to check the baby&rsquo;s ears for infections.)</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK,&rdquo; I said, but we both forgot.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 12</em><br />
I remembered to look in Violet&rsquo;s ear. Inside was a small dead cockroach, curled on its back.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s strange to see a dead roach in your wife&rsquo;s ear. A little scene in there &mdash; like looking in a Viewmaster.</p>

<p>Violet tried to extract it, failed, and agreed to see a doctor.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 15</em><br />
Violet is procrastinating about going to the doctor. Meanwhile, as I was meditating tonight at 1:00 a.m., I felt a cockroach in <em>my</em> ear. It crawled deeper and deeper, perhaps into my brain. (Does the brain connect with the ear? I wasn&rsquo;t sure.)</p>

<p>I continued meditating and found myself speaking mentally to the insect: &ldquo;Turn around! That&rsquo;s a good roach!&rdquo;</p>

<p>Not that I <em>believe</em> in talking to roaches.</p>

<p>When I finished my meditation, I asked Violet, &ldquo;Are you awake?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Can you look in my ear?&rdquo;</p>

<p>She looked in my ear. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a hair,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s touching your eardrum.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Now I&rsquo;m in the Bellevue emergency room, waiting for a doctor. It&rsquo;s 2:30 am. I was hoping there would be no line on a quiet winter night, but I forgot that the homeless come here to stay warm. So thirty-eight men and one woman are waiting with me as an infomercial plays on the television above us: &ldquo;I made a fortune investing in real estate. So can you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Once in a while the police pass through with a young, handcuffed criminal. They walk right in without waiting.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>After two hours and forty-five minutes, I got to see a doctor. &ldquo;What seems to be the problem?&rdquo; he asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I have a hair in my ear,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Um hmm.&rdquo; He got a speculum and looked inside.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re right. There&rsquo;s something in there. It looks like a hair.&rdquo; (But to another doctor, he muttered, &ldquo;It isn&rsquo;t a hair.&rdquo;)</p>

<p>&ldquo;It might be a cockroach,&rdquo; I volunteered. &ldquo;My wife has a cockroach in her ear.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why doesn&rsquo;t she take it out?&rdquo; the doctor asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;She&rsquo;s been busy.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The doctor looked in my ear again. &ldquo;It looks like a cockroach,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I saw it moving.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Really?&rdquo; I said. I felt a cockroach in me. I felt it move.</p>

<p>Another doctor came to look. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t see anything,&rdquo; he said.</p>

<p>My doctor put a long Q-tip in my ear. He pulled it out. Nothing was on it. He handed me the Q-tip. &ldquo;<em>You</em> try it. You can feel it in there.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I put it in. The two doctors watched. I pulled out the Q-tip. A tiny cat hair was on the end.</p>

<p>The doctors looked disappointed.</p>

<p>One took the Q-tip with the hair. &ldquo;Can I throw it out, or do you want to keep it as a souvenir?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Throw it out,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>They gave me a bill for $295, and I left.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 17</em><br />
I am going to begin killing the roaches with my own two hands.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 22</em><br />
I killed my first roach. It was a baby that crawled out of my novel when I opened it.</p>

<p>It took me five tries to kill it. They have very hard skins.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I admitted to Violet that I&rsquo;m killing the roaches.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So am I,&rdquo; she said sheepishly. &ldquo;Though I feel guilty about it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t mind them if they didn&rsquo;t crawl into our ears.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well, they haven&rsquo;t crawled into <em>your</em> ears.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;We don&rsquo;t know. Maybe they crawl in and crawl out.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 23</em><br />
Soon after I killed the first roach, the others began running faster when I approached. They must have a sophisticated communication network between the living and the dead.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>Since then, I&rsquo;ve cataloged a number of roach species: a dark-colored one, a squat one, a long, thin one.</p>

<p>Strange I&rsquo;d never noticed them before. You don&rsquo;t really <em>see</em> something until you kill it.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>March 26</em><br />
I came home late from work and Violet said, &ldquo;The house is clean, isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes, it is!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I killed a lot of cockroaches,&rdquo; she said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, yeah? How did it feel?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Terrible. When I killed a little one, I would think, &lsquo;That&rsquo;s someone&rsquo;s baby.&rsquo;&nbsp;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes, but I doubt the mothers love their babies as much as you do.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;And when I killed a big one, I thought, &lsquo;Maybe it&rsquo;s a pregnant one,&rsquo; and felt horribly guilty.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We hugged.</p>

<p><br />
<em>March 28</em><br />
I keep the Jewish Sabbath, and I&rsquo;ve decided not to kill roaches on that day. On the Sabbath, I feel I&rsquo;m in the palm of God&rsquo;s hand.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>May 28</em><br />
I began killing roaches again at the sink out of frustration. But in the middle of my death spree, I remembered Darwin&rsquo;s Theory of Natural Selection.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Wait a second,&rdquo; I told my wife. &ldquo;If I kill all the slow ones, only the fast ones will survive, and we&rsquo;ll have the fastest roaches on earth!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>June 17</em><br />
Violet, Sylvia, and I took a trip to Israel. I was struck by the utter buglessness of our Tel Aviv hotel, though it was in a hot, Middle Eastern country.</p>

<p>A great deal of poison must be responsible, I thought with a shudder.</p>

<p>Also, the room felt lonely &mdash; there was no one in it but us.</p>
														</div>


				
